# [E] Ephemeral — Generated Code Is Regenerated, Not Patched

If a file is generated, fix the source and regenerate. Never patch the output.

## How to Identify Generated Files

A file is generated if:
- It has a header comment: `// @generated`, `# Generated by`, `// DO NOT EDIT`, `// Code generated`
- Its path is in a `generated/`, `gen/`, `__generated__/`, or `.generated/` directory
- Its path matches a `full-autonomy` rule in `clear/autonomy.yml` with a reason mentioning generation

## What To Do Instead of Editing

| Want to change | Right approach |
|----------------|----------------|
| A generated TypeScript type | Update the source (Pydantic model, proto, OpenAPI) and regenerate |
| A generated React component | Update the protobuf or template and re-run the generation skill |
| A generated mock | Update the OpenAPI/proto contract and regenerate mocks |
| A Zod schema | Update the Pydantic model it derives from, regenerate |

## Regeneration Skills

Check `clear/examples/skills/` for documented example regeneration workflows:
- `type-sync.md` — Keep Python ↔ TypeScript types in sync
- `proto-visualization.md` — Update UI components from protobuf changes
- `api-endpoint.md` — Generate an endpoint with rate limiting and tests
- `reality-test.md` — Generate reality tests against an external service

New skills belong in `clear/templates/skills/`.

## When Asked to Modify a Generated File

Respond with:

> This file appears to be generated (`[reason]`). I'll fix the source and regenerate rather than editing it directly.
>
> Source to update: `[source file]`
> Regeneration command: `[command or skill name]`
>
> Should I proceed?

## Setting Up Regeneration

When creating a new generated file type:
1. Write a skill file in `clear/templates/skills/` documenting how to regenerate it
2. Add the regeneration command to `clear/verify-local.sh` (under build checks)
3. Add an architecture test that detects drift between source and generated output
